# iterate through dataframe
for i, row in tweets.iterrows():
    # remove any characters in the text that can't be displayed
    cur_string = row['text']
    tweets.at[i, 'text'] = re.sub(r'[^\w]', ' ', cur_string)
    
    # convert created_at strings to datetime format
    tweets.at[i, 'created_at'] = pd.to_datetime(row['created_at'], format = '%m-%d-%Y %H:%M:%S', errors = 'ignore')

# sort the dataframe by date (because it was reverse sorted before)    
tweets = tweets.sort_values(by = ['created_at'])

# drop the last 4 rows because they do not have timestamps
tweets = tweets.drop(tweets.tail(4).index)

# I want to create a wordcloud of Trump's tweets so we can get an idea of what he tweets about.

# These four strings will hold all of the words in his tweets over four intervals: before he ran for president, while he was
# running for president, while he was the president-elect, and after he was inaugurated.
pre_campaign_str = ""
candidacy_str = ""
president_elect_str = ""
president_str = ""

# The three major dates that will separate the data
announcement_date = datetime.date(2015, 6, 16)
election_date = datetime.date(2016, 11, 8)
inauguration_date = datetime.date(2017, 1, 20)

# add the text of each tweet to its respective string
for i, row in tweets.iterrows():
    if row['created_at'].date() < announcement_date:
        pre_campaign_str = pre_campaign_str + " " + row['text']
    elif row['created_at'].date() < election_date:
        candidacy_str = candidacy_str + " " + row['text']
    elif row['created_at'].date() < inauguration_date:
        president_elect_str = president_elect_str + " " + row['text']
    else:
        president_str = president_str + " " + row['text']
In [132]:
# create wordcloud
pre_campaign_wordcloud = WordCloud(width = 800, height = 800, margin = 0, max_words = 50).generate(pre_campaign_str)
 
# display wordcloud
plt.figure(figsize = (9, 9))
plt.imshow(pre_campaign_wordcloud, interpolation = 'bilinear')
plt.axis("off")
plt.margins(x = 0, y = 0)
plt.title("Tweeting Prior to Running for President (2009 to June 2015)")
plt.show()

# get a list of dates on which Trump tweeted

tweet_datetimes = tweets['created_at'].unique()
tweet_dates = []

# create a list of all unique dates on which a tweet was posted
for timestamp in tweet_datetimes:
    if not timestamp.date() in tweet_dates:
        tweet_dates.append(timestamp.date())

# create dataframe with one row for each date with a tweet
tweets_by_date = pd.DataFrame(tweet_dates, columns = ['date'])
tweets_by_date = tweets_by_date.set_index('date')
tweets_by_date['num_tweets'] = 0

# count the number of tweets on each day
for i, row in tweets.iterrows():
    tweets_by_date.at[row['created_at'].date(), 'num_tweets'] += 1
    
tweets_by_date.head()
